{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1778729667,"nonce":"zoFctfb86BDznonEFpZB390IMUE=","title":"Operationalise the must-do experiment recommended by the 2026-05-13 Codex consultation (parent: `0b1f109`). This issue is the experimental-design parent; it bundles the implementation child `020a65b` (full-state ε adversary class) together with the gating prerequisites `89891ab` (PGD inner-step verification), `6ec6b19` (cs2019 (t/N)^6 cost schedule), and `daa48c8` (bimodal-replicate analysis), plus the cheap pre-compute audit `b6084c7`. Do not re-litigate the framing here — see `0b1f109` body + comments `0cbb19f`, `0dbf19f`, `0bbb15f` for the full reasoning. This issue is the *plan*.","message":"Headline experiment: a matched-objective Riccati round-trip test. Train a linear LTV regulator on the production point-mass plant under a free time-varying full-state ε adversary with L2 budget over the rollout, evaluated against the cs_faithful Riccati controller built from the same plant/cost. Only if the linear regulator recovers the Riccati Δv signature do we proceed to a single GRU arm.\n\n\nCheap, no-new-training, BLOCKING for compute launch. Runs against existing checkpoints (no work yet started — `results/b6084c7/` does not exist). The audit must produce `results/b6084c7/notes/2026-05-12_trajectory_cost_audit.md` (per the issue body) and verify, for each of the four controllers (baseline GRU `f47abb1`'s `lit__post_nojerk` warmup-only winner; flavor-B GRU from `c723082`; trained LTV regulator from `410d7ac` `linear_regulator__adversarial`; analytical Riccati from `cs_faithful_pointmass`):\n\n- Plant config: damping, τ, mass, dt, state dim, delay handling\n- Cost: Q schedule shape, R, terminal cost, horizon\n- Adversary class actually optimised against\n- Task input channels (target_pos, target_vel, hold flag, target_on, SISU)\n- Loss-term breakdown active during training\n- Catch-trial probability\n\nOutput: side-by-side table flagging every axis on which the four controllers differ. Those axes are the matching targets for the Phase 1 spec below. **The audit can run in parallel with the Phase 1 adversary-class implementation, but no Phase 1 training is launched until the audit table is in `results/b6084c7/notes/`.**\n\n\nA new `FullStateEpsilonAdversary` class in `src/rlrmp/adversary.py` and a paired feedbax intervenor (full-state additive injection on the augmented state, not on the force port).\n\n\n- **ε is per-timestep, free, time-varying.** ε_t ∈ ℝ^n per step where n is the augmented-state dimension of the production plant. Trained via PGD with the same outer-loop structure as `LinearDynamicsAdversary`. Storage: `epsilon: Float[Array, \"T n_state\"]` directly on the eqx.Module.\n- **Budget: integrated L2 over rollout** — `∑_t ‖ε_t‖² ≤ E`. Matches the C\u0026S Eq. 13 reading (issue `0b1f109` comment `0dbf19f`). Projection: rescale the full (T·n)-flat vector if its L2 norm exceeds √E; otherwise pass through. Implemented as a single norm + `jnp.minimum`-based scale, analogous to `_frobenius_project`.\n- **SISU coupling**: budget at SISU=1 is `E_max`; at runtime scale by SISU via the intervenor's `params.scale = SISU` field (same pattern `LinearDynamicsAdversary` uses, `src/rlrmp/adversary.py` line 206). Per-trial SISU values come from the existing task pipeline.\n- **Hook point**: a new feedbax intervenor `FullStateAdditivePerturb` that lives in `feedbax/intervene/intervene.py` alongside `DynamicsMatrixPerturb`. It adds `ε_t` directly to *all* augmented state components at the post-mechanics step — NOT through the force port. This is the structural difference from `FixedField` (force-channel only) and from `DynamicsMatrixPerturb` (force = mass·ΔA·x, force-channel only). Implementing the full-state hook in feedbax is part of this issue's scope (per the project's \"near-integration with feedbax\" rule in CLAUDE.md). Wire it via the `PLANT_INTERVENOR_LABEL` swap pattern in `scripts/train_minimax.py` line 685+.\n- **PGD inner-loop**: reuse the fused inner-loop machinery from `train_minimax.py` lines 1069+ (`LinearDynamicsAdversary` path). Storage of ε per trial: replicated across the batch dim (same ε applied to all trials in a batch — adversary sees the trial structure via the projection-bounded budget and target geometry). Per-replicate adversary parameters (one ε array per controller replicate), matching the existing vmap layout.\n- **Default budget**: TBD, calibrated to give γ ≈ 1.5 γ* analogous to the cs2019 regime. Initial calibration runs at E ∈ {0.1, 0.3, 1.0, 3.0} (smoke-test before main run).\n\n\n- Library: `rlrmp.adversary.FullStateEpsilonAdversary` (capability-named per CLAUDE.md script-placement rules).\n- Intervenor: `feedbax.intervene.FullStateAdditivePerturb` (companion to `DynamicsMatrixPerturb`).\n- CLI: `--adversary-type full_state_epsilon`.\n\n\nAfter Phase 1 / Phase 2 training, run a held-out adversary search against each frozen controller. Same adversary class, fresh random init, PGD with {5, 20, 50} steps and 5 independent restarts per step-count. Report: held-out loss vs trained loss, ε trajectory similarity (cosine between trained and held-out worst-case ε), Δv under held-out ε vs trained ε. If held-out loss substantially exceeds trained loss (\u003e20%), the trained adversary was *not* worst-case and downstream Δv interpretation is unreliable — surface this as Phase-1-gate-failure-mode-3 (below).\n\n\nThis is the load-bearing decision. The brief's open question: do we use the b399efc-winning `movement_ramp__power6_dur80` schedule (zero in hold, power-6 ramp over 80 movement steps) — which is empirically best for warmup convergence on the production plant (k=10, τ=50ms, 140 steps) — or the cs2019 `(t/N)^6` full-trial schedule from `cs_eq15_cost_schedule` (1.0e6 on pos, 1.0e5 on vel, with the (t+1)/T ramp from t=0, on a 60-step horizon, k=0.1, τ=66ms)?\n\n**Resolution: use the cs2019 schedule + cs_faithful_pointmass plant for the Riccati gate.** Rationale:\n- The Riccati round-trip must be against a Riccati controller. `cs_faithful_pointmass` + `cs_eq15_cost_schedule` is the only place where the analytical Δv numbers (~+7-8% on the 8-state plant with delay) are known with confidence (audit `/tmp/flavor_ab_review/findings/cs_alignment_audit.md`, Bug `9a0558e`).\n- The production-plant decision records `a04711e` (k=10) and `08c49e3` (τ=50ms) are training-side defaults; they do not preempt a one-off matched experiment.\n- The conflict surfaced by the brief is real: production training + b399efc winner uses `movement_ramp`, NOT power-6 (t/N)^α. These schedules are not equivalent. Running cs2019's exact schedule on the production plant (k=10) is a meaningful Δv test, but if the linear regulator fails to match the *analytical* Riccati on cs2019's plant, we cannot diagnose whether the failure is plant or schedule. Better to match both plant and schedule against cs_faithful first.\n\n**Plant + schedule for Phase 1:**\n- `plant = cs_faithful_pointmass()` (defaults: mass=1, k=0.1 Ns/m, τ=0.066 s, dt=0.01 s, disturbance_integrator=True, delay_steps=5). State dim = 48 (8 phys + 5·8 lag).\n- `schedule = apply_delay_distribution_to_schedule(cs_eq15_cost_schedule(n_steps=60, state_dim=8), delay_steps=5)`. R = I_2.\n- Horizon: 60 steps × dt=0.01s = 0.6 s. No catch trials. No held-out hold/target-on epochs — the cs2019 game is a movement-only finite-horizon LQ-game, not a delayed-reach task.\n\n**Training entry-point:** A new shim script `scripts/train_round_trip.py` (cross-cutting per CLAUDE.md §\"Script placement\"): builds the cs_faithful plant/cost via `rlrmp.train.minimax.build_hps`-equivalent code, wires the FullStateEpsilonAdversary, dispatches `--hidden-type linear` or `--hidden-type gru`. Reuses the existing minimax outer loop from `train_minimax.py` where possible; do NOT fork it. If the existing `train_minimax.py` cannot accept a `cs_faithful` task without invasive changes, the shim builds the task directly and calls the same training primitives via `rlrmp.train.minimax`. **OPEN: see open-questions §3.**\n\n**γ target:** γ = 1.5 γ* per the synthesis recommendation. Compute γ* via `find_gamma_star` on the cs_faithful plant + cs_eq15_cost_schedule first. Budget E = (peak ε under Riccati worst-case) calibrated from the Riccati solution, so that the trained adversary has the same L2 budget as the Riccati's worst-case ε* trajectory. **OPEN: see open-questions §6.**\n\n\n- **Model**: `--hidden-type linear` (LTV regulator `u_t = -K_t · e_t` per `scripts/train_minimax.py` line 1712 doc).\n- **n_replicates**: 5 (matches production default). Bimodality clustering needs at least 5 to be meaningful; 5 is the floor.\n- **Warmup**: train without adversary for ~2000 batches against the matched cs_faithful task with no ε. Verify the warmed-up regulator converges close to the LQR (γ → ∞) Riccati K.\n- **Adversarial phase**: switch to FullStateEpsilonAdversary, 8000 batches, PGD inner-step = 5 (default). After Phase-1 success, sweep PGD ∈ {5, 20, 50} as the `89891ab` audit (re-run training? or re-run inner-loop on a saved adversary against the frozen trained controller? — the latter is preferable for compute. Specifically: freeze the trained K_t, replace the adversary with a fresh random ε, run PGD for N steps at each restart, compare worst-case loss against the trained-adversary loss).\n- **Success criterion (gate)**: trained K_t closely matches the analytical Riccati K_t* (e.g. `‖K_trained - K_riccati‖_F / ‖K_riccati‖_F \u003c tolerance`). Tolerance is loose; cs2019's regime gives analytical Δv ≈ +7-8% so trained linear should give Δv in the same direction, ideally in the +1% to +15% range on a 15 cm forward reach evaluated under nominal ε=0. **Quantitative threshold: trained-linear Δv \u003e +1% with 95% CI overlapping the analytical Riccati Δv.** If trained Δv is \u003c 0 or \u003e +30%, gate fails.\n- **Failure modes** (decision tree):\n  - **Mode 1 (linear ≪ Riccati)**: training/eval pipeline is not the H∞ game. Stop. Diagnose: plant mismatch? cost mismatch? adversary class mismatch? PGD not converging? Open follow-up issue tagged blocker.\n  - **Mode 2 (linear ≫ Riccati, e.g. +50%)**: regulator is overshooting Riccati; possibly the PGD adversary is not finding worst-case (test via `89891ab` held-out audit). If held-out adversary loss \u003e trained loss substantially, see Mode 3.\n  - **Mode 3 (held-out adversary stronger than trained)**: trained adversary is not worst-case. Don't trust Δv. Re-train with stronger PGD (50 inner steps).\n  - **Mode 4 (linear matches Riccati on K_t but Δv is off)**: numerical issue in the evaluation pipeline. Diagnose against the `b6084c7` audit table.\n\n\n- **Model**: `--hidden-type gru`, `hidden_size=180`, `population_structure` default (matches production).\n- **n_replicates**: 5. Bimodality is the explicit reporting concern (see Phase 5).\n- **Training schedule**: identical to Phase 3 — same plant, same cost, same adversary, same budget. The whole point is to keep everything matched except architecture.\n- **Warmup**: 2000 batches without ε, then 8000 with full adversary. The cs_faithful plant + delayed-reach mismatch may cause warmup convergence issues — see open-questions §4.\n- **Success criterion**: GRU either matches the linear-regulator Δv signature (+ve, replicate-conditioned) OR shows a clean dissociation (e.g. preserved induced-gain modulation under held-out ε but flat nominal Δv). Both outcomes are scientifically informative per the synthesis. **A null Δv with no held-out feedback-gain inflation would indicate the GRU is dropping the adversary signal entirely** — a third outcome that is informative but requires the held-out audit (Phase 1 protocol) to diagnose.\n\n\nFor both arms (linear and GRU), per replicate, compute:\n\n| Signature | Definition | Source |\n|---|---|---|\n| Δv (nominal) | Peak forward velocity on a 15 cm forward reach, ε=0, vs the baseline (matched cs_faithful regulator trained without adversary) | `rlrmp.eval.kinematics` |\n| Δv (held-out ε) | Peak forward velocity under independent strong-adversary search | New: needs Phase 1 held-out infrastructure |\n| Feedback-gain step-response | Impulse perturbation at trial midpoint, measure peak corrective force / peak velocity deflection | New code: extends `rlrmp.eval.pert`-style pipeline |\n| Induced gain by channel | `additive_force`, `sensory_perturbation`, `structural_da`, and **NEW: `full_state_epsilon`** (extends `_W_CHANNELS` in `induced_gain.py`) | `rlrmp.analysis.induced_gain` |\n| Endpoint / lateral deviation | Terminal position error in fwd \u0026 lat axes, mean ± SD over directions | `rlrmp.eval.kinematics` |\n| Held-out adversary loss | Loss under strong independent adversary | New: held-out adversary CLI helper |\n\n**Replicate-conditioned reporting**: per CLAUDE.md plotting rules (profile_comparison_grid with shared y-axes). Cluster replicates by `(Δv, final_loss, induced_gain_full_state_epsilon)` triple using scikit-learn GaussianMixture (n_components=2). Report cluster means + per-replicate scatter, never the bare group mean (per `daa48c8`).\n\n**New code required for `daa48c8`**: a small `rlrmp.analysis.replicate_clustering` module exposing a function that takes a multi-signature DataFrame (one row per replicate) and returns cluster labels + per-cluster summary. This is reusable across all future replicate-based reporting. Add to the library, not the experiment script (per CLAUDE.md script-placement rules).\n\n**Extension to `induced_gain.py`**: add `W_FULL_STATE_EPSILON = \"full_state_epsilon\"` and the corresponding `Bw_raw` construction in `linearise_trajectory` (full-state additive =\u003e Bw = I_n at every timestep). Update `_W_CHANNELS`.\n\n\n- **Per training run**: linear regulator on cs_faithful 60-step horizon should be very fast (linear model, small state). Estimate ~5-10 min on a 5090. GRU on same plant: ~30-60 min for 10k batches at batch_size=250.\n- **Total compute**: linear regulator (1 run × 5 replicates, fused vmap) + GRU (1 run × 5 replicates, fused vmap) + held-out adversary audit (run on frozen models, ~10 min each) + PGD step-count sweep on trained linear (3 step-counts × 5 restarts on frozen model, ~5 min each) ≈ 2-3 hours on a single 5090. Estimated cost: $2-3.\n- **Pre-compute audit**: ~2 hours of human/agent analysis time on existing artifacts. No GPU.\n\n\n| Outcome | Action |\n|---|---|\n| Phase 0 audit reveals plant/cost mismatch across the 4 controllers | Resolve mismatch before Phase 1. Specifically: align Phase 1 spec to whichever axis is canonical. |\n| Phase 3 (linear) succeeds (Δv \u003e +1%, matches Riccati K) | Proceed to Phase 4 (GRU). |\n| Phase 3 (linear) fails Mode 1 | Stop. The pipeline is not the H∞ game. Diagnose; new follow-up issue. |\n| Phase 3 (linear) fails Mode 2/3 (PGD audit) | Retry training with PGD steps = 50. If still fails, treat as Mode 1. |\n| Phase 4 (GRU) recovers Δv | Decoupling NOT confirmed in architecture; GRU is capable. Open `0c95d6b` to investigate HOW it does so. |\n| Phase 4 (GRU) dissociates (held-out gain ↑ but nominal Δv flat) | Decoupling-via-architecture confirmed empirically. Open `0c95d6b` with the standardized-perturbation caveat (below). |\n| Phase 4 (GRU) collapses (null Δv AND null held-out gain) | GRU is dropping adversary signal. Diagnose training; possibly increase PGD strength. |\n\n\nIf Phase 4 yields the dissociation pattern (GRU preserves feedback-gain modulation under held-out ε but shows flat nominal Δv), that pattern IS the empirical signature of decoupling. At that point `0c95d6b` becomes valuable: investigate HOW the GRU decouples via affine decomposition of u(x, t).\n\n**Codex's caveat (must propagate into `0c95d6b`'s spec)**: `0c95d6b`'s current body specifies measuring the local feedback Jacobian on \"a clean undisturbed reach.\" This is degenerate — on x_nom(t) with no perturbation the perturbation-correction signal is zero by construction. The decomposition must be measured under **standardized small perturbations** (impulse responses, sensory step changes, motor noise injection) where the feedback-correction signal is non-zero. Before opening any decomposition work, update `0c95d6b` to require: (i) standardized perturbation protocol; (ii) measurement of K_local(t) via Jacobians along *perturbed* trajectories; (iii) decomposition of u into ‖u_nom‖² (on x_nom) and ‖u_correction‖² (on x_perturbed − x_nom). Comment on `0c95d6b` with this requirement when opening the follow-up.\n\n\n1. **OPEN — Does Phase 1 use the production plant (k=10, τ=50ms, 140-step delayed-reach) AT ALL, or only the cs_faithful plant?** This plan defaults to cs_faithful for Phase 1/3 because that's where the Riccati gate is computable. But the user may want a follow-up Phase 1b on the production plant after the gate passes, to bridge to the production-side b399efc work. I have NOT included Phase 1b in this plan; it is a deferred follow-up if the user wants it. Decision needed: file Phase 1b as a separate issue now, or wait until Phase 4 results land?\n\n2. **OPEN — Budget L2 specification: rollout-integrated `∑‖ε_t‖² ≤ E` (the synthesis reading) vs per-step `‖ε_t‖ ≤ E` (peak constraint) vs both?** The plan assumes rollout-integrated only, matching cs2019 Eq. 13 H∞ L2 game. But the FullStateEpsilonAdversary class could trivially support both; per-step budgets are how curl-field training is typically run. Decision needed before adversary class is implemented.\n\n3. **OPEN — Can `train_minimax.py` accept a cs_faithful task without invasive changes?** The current `build_hps` in `rlrmp.train.minimax` hardcodes the production task config (`center_out_delayed_reach`, k=10, τ=0.05, n_steps=140). The Phase 1 Riccati round-trip needs cs_faithful (k=0.1, τ=0.066, n_steps=60, no delayed-reach epochs, no catch trials). Options: (a) add a `--task-preset cs_faithful` flag to `train_minimax.py`; (b) build a new entry-point `scripts/train_round_trip.py` that constructs the task directly and reuses `rlrmp.train.minimax` library primitives. (b) is cleaner per CLAUDE.md script-placement (cross-cutting CLI entry-points stay in `scripts/`). Decision needed: confirm (b) is the right path, or specify (a).\n\n4. **OPEN — How does the cs_faithful task work without a delayed-reach hold epoch?** The current production task has hold (0-1 steps) + target_on (10-30 steps) + movement epochs. cs2019's game is a finite-horizon LQ-game with no hold, no go-cue. The GRU is trained on delayed-reach by design. Forcing it onto a hold-free 60-step horizon may break the SISU input wiring and the catch-trial machinery. Decision needed: do we (a) drop hold/catch entirely for Phase 4 GRU, accepting that the GRU is trained on a different task than production; or (b) add a minimal hold+go-cue structure to the cs_faithful task, adapting the cost schedule to start at go-cue rather than t=0? (a) is what cs2019 actually models; (b) is closer to production. The synthesis is silent on this. I lean (a) since the experiment is about whether the H∞ game works, not about replicating production.\n\n5. **OPEN — What baseline does Δv compare against?** For the cs_faithful regime, the analytical Δv is \"fwd peak velocity at γ=1.5γ* / fwd peak velocity at γ→∞\" (i.e., H∞ vs LQR on the same plant/cost). For trained models, we need to define the matched baseline. Two candidates: (i) the trained linear/GRU on the same plant+cost+task WITHOUT the adversarial phase (warmup-only); (ii) the analytical LQR Riccati from the same plant+cost (γ→∞ limit of cs_faithful Riccati). Choice affects what Δv \"matches Riccati\" means.\n\n6. **OPEN — Adversary budget calibration**: how do we set `E_max`? Options: (i) match the Riccati worst-case ε* trajectory L2 norm on the cs_faithful plant at γ=1.5γ*; (ii) set `E_max = 1.0` (arbitrary scalar, sweep later); (iii) calibrate from physical intuition (max ε ≈ peak nominal force). Decision needed for the Phase 1 implementation defaults.\n\n7. **OPEN — Per-replicate vs single-adversary**: should we keep one adversary per replicate (matching production minimax), or use a single shared adversary across replicates (cleaner game structure)? Per-replicate matches the existing `LinearDynamicsAdversary` pattern; single-adversary is closer to a clean H∞ game. The synthesis recommendation does not specify, but Codex's \"independent restarts\" framing suggests multiple adversaries should be evaluated against the same controller for the held-out audit, independent of training-time structure.\n\n\n- **Parent (decision frame)**: `0b1f109` synthesis + comments `00bb11f`, `0cbb19f`, `0dbf19f`, `0bbb15f`\n- **Implementation child kept open**: `020a65b` (full-state ε adversary class — this issue's Phase 1)\n- **Bundled prerequisites (folded into this experiment)**: `89891ab` (PGD step-count sweep — Phase 1 + 3 held-out audit), `6ec6b19` (cost-schedule (t/N)^6 — Phase 2 resolved to cs_eq15_cost_schedule), `daa48c8` (bimodal-replicate analysis — Phase 5 clustering)\n- **Pre-compute audit (BLOCKING)**: `b6084c7`\n- **Phase umbrella**: `f695729` (regulator-coupling phase)\n- **Decision records (constraints)**: `a04711e` (k=10 damping — applies to production plant only, this experiment uses cs_faithful), `08c49e3` (τ=50ms — same)\n- **Reference flavor-B numbers**: `c723082` comment `c87b273` (mean Δv ≈ −25%, bimodal +40% / −25% replicate split)\n- **Matrix-winner warmup reference**: `b399efc` (`movement_ramp__power6_dur80`, warmup-only, NOT adversarial — production schedule for comparison)\n- **Riccati infrastructure**: `src/rlrmp/analysis/hinf_riccati.py` `cs_faithful_pointmass`, `cs_eq15_cost_schedule`, `apply_delay_distribution_to_schedule`, `solve_hinf_riccati`, `find_gamma_star`\n- **Adversary infrastructure**: `src/rlrmp/adversary.py` (`GaussianBumpAdversary`, `LinearDynamicsAdversary` patterns), `src/rlrmp/adversarial_training.py` (`_inject_adversary_forces`, `_inject_adversary_delta_A`), `scripts/train_minimax.py` (fused PGD inner-loop, lines 1069+)\n- **Feedbax-side change**: new `FullStateAdditivePerturb` intervenor in `feedbax/intervene/intervene.py`, companion to `DynamicsMatrixPerturb` (line 171+) and `FixedField` (line 138+). Must derive from `Component`, hook at the post-mechanics step.\n- **Coord cross-refs (one-line)**: `c99ad9d` (training-methods coord — comment after Phase 1 lands), `4d38c15` (analyses coord — comment after Phase 5 multi-signature pipeline lands), `b33e8da` (phases coord — already indexed under `f695729`)\n- **Decoupling follow-up after success**: `0c95d6b` (Tier 1 GRU affine decomposition) — REQUIRES SPEC UPDATE before opening (see Next steps section above)\n\nCo-authored-by: Claude Opus 4.7 \u003cnoreply@anthropic.com\u003e","files":null}]}